Here are some fun facts about black cats!

- In ancient Egypt, all cats (including black ones) were considered sacred and linked to the goddess Bastet. Killing a cat, even accidentally, could be punishable by death.

- In Japan, black cats are seen as good luck, especially for single women â theyâre believed to attract suitors. The famous âmaneki-nekoâ (beckoning cat) figurines often come in black for this reason.

- Sailors loved black cats: they believed a black cat on board brought good luck and ensured a safe return home. Some fishermenâs wives even kept black cats at home to protect their husbands at sea.

- Black cats have a natural âstealth modeâ: their solid black fur (caused by high levels of melanin) makes them harder to spot at night, which is why theyâre sometimes called âpanthers in miniature.â

- The gene that makes cats completely black is dominant, but thereâs a rare condition called âmelanistic tabbyâ where black cats still have faint ghost stripes visible in bright sunlight.

- October 27 is officially National Black Cat Day in the UK (and celebrated in many places) to help boost adoption rates, since black cats are often the last to be adopted from shelters due to old superstitions.

- Bombay cats, the sleek all-black breed that looks like a mini panther, were deliberately bred in the 1950s to resemble a black leopard.

Despite the âbad luckâ myth in some Western cultures, black cats have been symbols of fortune, protection, and mystery for most of history! ð¾â«
